{"title_page": "Banditry in Chile", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n[[Image:ElHuasoYLaLavandera.jpg|thumb|''The Huaso and the Washerwoman'' by [[Mauricio Rugendas]] (1835)]]\n[[Banditry]] ({{lang-es|bandidaje}}) was a considerable phenomenon in 19th century and early 20th century [[Central Chile]] and [[Araucan\u00eda (historic region)|Araucan\u00eda]]. Many bandits achieved legendary status for their brutality and others for being regarded [[folk hero]]es.<ref name=Membandidaje/> The bandits usually preyed on [[hacienda]]s and their [[inquilino]]s.<ref name=Membandidaje/> \n\nThe [[Chilean War of Independence]] (1810\u20131826) shaped an era of banditry as the war transitioned into irregular warfare known as [[Guerra a muerte]] (1819\u20131821) which was particularly destructive for the [[Biob\u00edo Region|Biob\u00edo area]] and ended only to see a period of outlaw banditry occur until the late 1820s.<ref name=villalobosindep>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, pp. 406\u2013413.</ref> The rise of banditry made travel dangerous indeed 1812 is held as the date from where safe travel between Concepci\u00f3n and Santiago was not longer safe for small groups.<ref name=salinas59>Salinas 1986, p. 59.</ref> The [[Pincheira brothers]], a royalist outlaw group based on indigenous territory east of the Andes was defeated and dissolved in 1832.<ref name=MembandidajeCRONO/> \n\nIn the words of [[Benjam\u00edn Vicu\u00f1a Mackenna]] banditry was a \"national plague, worse than lepra or cholera\".<ref name=salinas59/> Following Chilean victories in [[War of the Pacific]] against Peru veterans begun to return in 1881 leading to a surge in banditry.<ref name=MembandidajeCRONO>{{Cite journal| url   = http://www.memoriachilena.gob.cl/602/w3-article-560.html#cronologia\n| title = Bandidaje rural en Chile central (1820-1920): Cronolog\u00eda \n| work  = [[Memoria Chilena]]\n| publisher  = [[Biblioteca Nacional de Chile]]\n| accessdate = December 30, 2019\n| language = Spanish\n}}</ref> The return of the veterans coincided with the Chilean Army's crushing of [[Mapuche]] resistance in the [[Occupation of Araucan\u00eda]] (1861\u20131883). This led to opportunities bandits and veterans-turned-bandits to immigrate to the newly opened Aracan\u00eda territory,<ref name=salinas60>Salinas 1986, p. 60.</ref><ref name=MembandidajeCRONO/> leading to sudden rise in violence and in a region that was recovering from Chilean-Mapuche warfare.<ref name=cadiz/> Bandits that immigrated to Araucan\u00eda allied with displaced Mapuche and made cattle theft their chief business.<ref name=salinas60/> Stolen cattle was sold in marketplaces through the region.<ref name=salinas60/> \n\nThus Araucan\u00eda continued to be an insecure zone for many years.<ref name=cadiz>{{cite journal |last=C\u00e1diz Villarroel |first=Francisco Felipe |last2= |first2= |date=2013 |title=Chilenizaci\u00f3n institucional y progreso en Villarrica, Chile, 1900-1920 |url=http://www.redalyc.org/pdf/200/20025468005.pdf |journal=[[Procesos Hist\u00f3ricos]]|language=Spanish |publisher= |volume=XII |issue=23 |pages=58\u201373 |doi= |accessdate=5 December 2013}}</ref> [[Assault]]s and [[robbery]] were common in the region.<ref name=Ferrando620/> Because of this until the 1920s [[carbine]]s, [[revolver]]s and other firearms were common in the households of Araucan\u00eda.<ref name=Ferrando620>Ferrando 1986, p. 620</ref> Banditry in Araucan\u00eda and Central Chile was begun to be suppressed in the late 19th century with the creation of the rural police [[Cuerpo de Gendarmes para las Colonias]], a predecessor to Chile's main police force [[Carabineros de Chile]].<ref name=Membandidaje>{{Cite journal| url   = http://www.memoriachilena.cl/602/w3-article-560.html\n| title = Bandidaje rural en Chile central (1820-1920) \n| work  = [[Memoria Chilena]]\n| publisher  = [[Biblioteca Nacional de Chile]]\n| accessdate = December 30, 2019\n| language = Spanish\n}}</ref> [[Hern\u00e1n Trizano]] led this policing force until 1905.<ref name=carab>{{cite web |url=http://www.carabineros.cl/# |title=Historia de Carabineros de Chile |language=Spanish |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=Carabineros.cl |publisher= |accessdate=7 December 2013}}</ref> \n\n===Notable bandits===\n;Independence Era\n*[[Jos\u00e9 Miguel Neira]], leader of [[Los Neirinos]], patriots<ref name=salinas60/>\n*[[Pincheira brothers]], royalists\n;1835\u20131900\n*[[Juan de Dios L\u00f3pez]]<ref name=Membandidaje/> \n*the [[Mendoza brothers]]<ref name=Membandidaje/>\n*[[Ciriaco Contreras]]<ref name=Membandidaje/>\n*[[Pancho Falcato]]<ref name=Membandidaje/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mapuche conflict]]\n*[[Mapuche uprising of 1881]]\n*[[Pedro \u00d1anc\u00fapel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n;Bibliography\n*{{cite book |last=Ferrando Kaun |first=Ricardo |authorlink= |title=Y as\u00ed naci\u00f3 La Frontera...|url= |accessdate= |year=1986 |edition=Second |publisher=Editorial Ant\u00e1rtica |location= |isbn=978-956-7019-83-0 |page=}}\n*[[Sergio Villalobos|Villalobos, Sergio]]; Silva, Osvaldo; Silva, Fernando; Estelle, Patricio (1974). ''Historia De Chile'' (14th ed.). [[Editorial Universitaria]]. {{ISBN|956-11-1163-2}}.\n*{{cite journal |last1=Salinas |first1=Maximiliano A. |date=1986 |title=El bandolero chileno del siglo XIX: Su imagen en la sabidur\u00eda popular |url=http://www.bibliotecanacionaldigital.gob.cl/visor/BND:68533 |journal=Araucaria de Chile |volume= |issue= |pages=57\u201375|language=Spanish |doi= |access-date=December 21, 2019}}\n[[Category:19th century in Chile]]\n[[Category:20th century in Chile]]\n[[Category:20th-century crimes in Chile]]\n[[Category:Chilean outlaws]]\n[[Category:Occupation of Araucan\u00eda]]\n[[Category:Chilean War of Independence]]\n[[Category:Mapuche history]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n[[Image:ElHuasoYLaLavandera.jpg|thumb|''The Huaso and the Washerwoman'' by [[Mauricio Rugendas]] (1835)]]\n[[Banditry]] ({{lang-es|bandidaje}}) was a considerable phenomenon in 19th century and early 20th century [[Central Chile]] and [[Araucan\u00eda (historic region)|Araucan\u00eda]]. Many bandits achieved legendary status for their brutality and others for being regarded [[folk hero]]es.<ref name=Membandidaje/> The bandits usually preyed on [[hacienda]]s and their [[inquilino]]s.<ref name=Membandidaje/> \n\nThe [[Chilean War of Independence]] (1810\u20131826) shaped an era of banditry as the war transitioned into irregular warfare known as [[Guerra a muerte]] (1819\u20131821) which was particularly destructive for the [[Biob\u00edo Region|Biob\u00edo area]] and ended only to see a period of outlaw banditry occur until the late 1820s.<ref name=villalobosindep>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, pp. 406\u2013413.</ref> The rise of banditry made travel dangerous indeed 1812 is held as the date from where safe travel between Concepci\u00f3n and Santiago was not longer safe for small groups.<ref name=salinas59>Salinas 1986, p. 59.</ref> The [[Pincheira brothers]], a royalist outlaw group based on indigenous territory east of the Andes was defeated and dissolved in 1832.<ref name=MembandidajeCRONO/> \n\nIn the words of [[Benjam\u00edn Vicu\u00f1a Mackenna]] banditry was a \"national plague, worse than lepra or cholera\".<ref name=salinas59/> Following Chilean victories in [[War of the Pacific]] against Peru veterans begun to return in 1881 leading to a surge in banditry.<ref name=MembandidajeCRONO>{{Cite journal| url   = http://www.memoriachilena.gob.cl/602/w3-article-560.html#cronologia\n| title = Bandidaje rural en Chile central (1820-1920): Cronolog\u00eda \n| work  = [[Memoria Chilena]]\n| publisher  = [[Biblioteca Nacional de Chile]]\n| accessdate = December 30, 2019\n| language = Spanish\n}}</ref> The return of the veterans coincided with the Chilean Army's crushing of [[Mapuche]] resistance in the [[Occupation of Araucan\u00eda]] (1861\u20131883). This led to opportunities bandits and veterans-turner-bandits to immigrate to the newly opened Aracan\u00eda territory,<ref name=salinas60>Salinas 1986, p. 60.</ref><ref name=MembandidajeCRONO/> leading to sudden rise in violence and in a region that was recovering from Chilean-Mapuche warfare.<ref name=cadiz/> Bandits that immigrated to Araucan\u00eda allied with displaced Mapuche and made cattle theft their chief business.<ref name=salinas60/> Stolen cattle was sold in marketplaces through the region.<ref name=salinas60/> \n\nThus Araucan\u00eda continued to be an insecure zone for many years.<ref name=cadiz>{{cite journal |last=C\u00e1diz Villarroel |first=Francisco Felipe |last2= |first2= |date=2013 |title=Chilenizaci\u00f3n institucional y progreso en Villarrica, Chile, 1900-1920 |url=http://www.redalyc.org/pdf/200/20025468005.pdf |journal=[[Procesos Hist\u00f3ricos]]|language=Spanish |publisher= |volume=XII |issue=23 |pages=58\u201373 |doi= |accessdate=5 December 2013}}</ref> [[Assault]]s and [[robbery]] were common in the region.<ref name=Ferrando620/> Because of this until the 1920s [[carbine]]s, [[revolver]]s and other firearms were common in the households of Araucan\u00eda.<ref name=Ferrando620>Ferrando 1986, p. 620</ref> Banditry in Araucan\u00eda and Central Chile was begun to be suppressed in the late 19th century with the creation of the rural police [[Cuerpo de Gendarmes para las Colonias]], a predecessor to Chile's main police force [[Carabineros de Chile]].<ref name=Membandidaje>{{Cite journal| url   = http://www.memoriachilena.cl/602/w3-article-560.html\n| title = Bandidaje rural en Chile central (1820-1920) \n| work  = [[Memoria Chilena]]\n| publisher  = [[Biblioteca Nacional de Chile]]\n| accessdate = December 30, 2019\n| language = Spanish\n}}</ref> [[Hern\u00e1n Trizano]] led this policing force until 1905.<ref name=carab>{{cite web |url=http://www.carabineros.cl/# |title=Historia de Carabineros de Chile |language=Spanish |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=Carabineros.cl |publisher= |accessdate=7 December 2013}}</ref> \n\n===Notable bandits===\n;Independence Era\n*[[Jos\u00e9 Miguel Neira]], leader of [[Los Neirinos]], patriots<ref name=salinas60/>\n*[[Pincheira brothers]], royalists\n;1835\u20131900\n*[[Juan de Dios L\u00f3pez]]<ref name=Membandidaje/> \n*the [[Mendoza brothers]]<ref name=Membandidaje/>\n*[[Ciriaco Contreras]]<ref name=Membandidaje/>\n*[[Pancho Falcato]]<ref name=Membandidaje/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mapuche conflict]]\n*[[Mapuche uprising of 1881]]\n*[[Pedro \u00d1anc\u00fapel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n;Bibliography\n*{{cite book |last=Ferrando Kaun |first=Ricardo |authorlink= |title=Y as\u00ed naci\u00f3 La Frontera...|url= |accessdate= |year=1986 |edition=Second |publisher=Editorial Ant\u00e1rtica |location= |isbn=978-956-7019-83-0 |page=}}\n*[[Sergio Villalobos|Villalobos, Sergio]]; Silva, Osvaldo; Silva, Fernando; Estelle, Patricio (1974). ''Historia De Chile'' (14th ed.). [[Editorial Universitaria]]. {{ISBN|956-11-1163-2}}.\n*{{cite journal |last1=Salinas |first1=Maximiliano A. |date=1986 |title=El bandolero chileno del siglo XIX: Su imagen en la sabidur\u00eda popular |url=http://www.bibliotecanacionaldigital.gob.cl/visor/BND:68533 |journal=Araucaria de Chile |volume= |issue= |pages=57\u201375|language=Spanish |doi= |access-date=December 21, 2019}}\n[[Category:19th century in Chile]]\n[[Category:20th century in Chile]]\n[[Category:20th-century crimes in Chile]]\n[[Category:Chilean outlaws]]\n[[Category:Occupation of Araucan\u00eda]]\n[[Category:Chilean War of Independence]]\n[[Category:Mapuche history]]\n", "name_user": "Sietecolores", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banditry_in_Chile"}
{"title_page": "Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics", "text_new": "{{short description|Norwegian/Swedish shipping company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Wallenius Wilhelmsen ASA\n| logo                = WalleniusWilhelmsen.png\n| image               = Torrens, Fremantle, 2015 (08).JPG\n| image_size          = \n| image_alt           = MV Torrens arriving at Fremantle, Australia, in June 2015\n| image_caption       = \n| type                = \n| foundation          = 1999\n| location            = [[Lysaker]], [[Norway]]\n| key_people          = \n| area_served         = \n| industry            = [[Shipping]]\n| products            = \n| revenue             = {{profit}} US$2.3 billion (2007)\n| operating_profit    = \n| net_operating_income = \n| num_employees       = 3,300 (2007)<ref name=facts/>\n| parent              = [[Wallenius Lines]]<br>[[Wilh. Wilhelmsen]]\n| subsid              = \n| homepage            = www.walleniuswilhelmsen.com/\n| footnotes           = <ref name=facts>{{cite web|url=http://www.2wglobal.com/www/aboutUs/companyFacts/companyFacts/index.jsp |title=Facts and Figures |publisher=Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics |accessdate=4 February 2009}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics''' is a privately owned [[Norway|Norwegian]]/[[Sweden|Swedish]] [[shipping company]], established in 1999 and co-owned by the two shipping companies [[Wallenius Lines]] and [[Wilh. Wilhelmsen]].<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2007 |title=Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics |encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget  |url=http://www.snl.no/article.html?id=10340445 }}</ref>\n\nThe company offers a range of logistics services, including [[supply chain management]], ocean transportation using [[Neo-bulk cargo]] ships,<ref name=\"WH\">[http://www.2wglobal.com/www/pdf/FleetInternet.pdf Fleet List] (from the Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics website. Accessed 2008-03-11.) [https://web.archive.org/web/20160924172047/http://www.2wglobal.com/globalassets/about-us/documents/fleet-list.pdf Archive]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.2wglobal.com/global-network/fleet/fleet-overview/fleet-list/ |title=Ocean Fleet List|accessdate=24 September 2016 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160920163838/http://www.2wglobal.com/global-network/fleet/fleet-overview/fleet-list/ |archive-date= 20 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wilhelmsenasa.com/aboutus/ourbusiness/thefleet/Pages/Fleetlist.aspx |title=Fleet list, ship details |publisher=|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref> terminal handling, inland distribution and [[technical management|technical services]]. It is one of the world's largest companies in the transporting of [[Roll-on/roll-off]] equipment: automobiles, heavy machinery (mining, construction, farming equipment), yachts, trains, power stations, trailers, [[Mafi roll trailer|Mafi roll trailers]] and others. Headquartered in [[Oslo]] and [[Stockholm]], with main regional offices in [[New York City|New York]], [[Tokyo]] and [[Melbourne]],{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}} the company has 3,300 employees worldwide.<ref name=facts/>\n\nOn 29 October 2008 Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics received the distinguished Norwegian American Trade Award for 2008 from the Norwegian-American Chamber of Commerce.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Norwegian American Trade Award for 2008 |url=http://www.norway.org/business/maritime/wwl.htm  |publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Norway)|Norwegian Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] |date=10 November 2008 |accessdate=20 November 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn '''2017''', Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics were split into Wallenius Wilhelmsen Ocean and Wallenius Wilhelmsen Solutions in the [[Wallenius Wilhelmsen|Wallenius Wilhelmsen Group]].\n\n{{Gallery|lines=3\n|File:Don Quijote.JPG|''Don Quijote'', a WWL [[car carrier]].\n|File:Wallenius Wilhelmsen.JPG|''Trianon'' in the [[Strait of Juan de Fuca]].\n|File:Ship passing through Panama Canal 01.jpg|[[RORO]] carrier ''Tourcoing'' passing through [[Panama canal]].\n}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Taiko (ship)]]\n*[[MV Tricolor]]\n*[[List of roll-on/roll-off vessel accidents]]\n*[[Wallenius Lines]]\n*[[Wilh. Wilhelmsen]]\n*[[American Roll-on Roll-off Carrier]]\n*[[EUKOR]]\n*[[United European Car Carriers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics}}\n*[http://www.2wglobal.com/ Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics official website]\n\n[[Category:1999 establishments in Norway]]\n[[Category:Car carrier shipping companies]]\n[[Category:Commercial management shipping companies]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics]]\n[[Category:Ro-ro shipping companies]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Norwegian/Swedish shipping company}}\n{{Infobox company \n| name   = Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics\n| logo   = WalleniusWilhelmsen.png\n| image         = Torrens, Fremantle, 2015 (08).JPG\n| image_size    = \n| image_alt     = MV Torrens arriving at Fremantle, Australia, in June 2015\n| image_caption = \n| type   = \n| foundation     = 1999\n| location       = [[Lysaker]], [[Norway]]\n| key_people     = \n| area_served    =\n| industry       = [[Shipping]]\n| products       = \n| revenue        = {{profit}} US$2.3 billion (2007)\n| operating_profit = \n| net_operating_income = \n| num_employees  = 3,300 (2007)<ref name=facts/>\n| parent         = [[Wallenius Lines]]<br>[[Wilh. Wilhelmsen]]\n| subsid         = \n| homepage       = [http://www.2wglobal.com/ www.2wglobal.com]\n| footnotes      = <ref name=facts>{{cite web|url=http://www.2wglobal.com/www/aboutUs/companyFacts/companyFacts/index.jsp |title=Facts and Figures |publisher=Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics |accessdate=4 February 2009}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics''' is a privately owned [[Norway|Norwegian]]/[[Sweden|Swedish]] [[shipping company]], established in 1999 and co-owned by the two shipping companies [[Wallenius Lines]] and [[Wilh. Wilhelmsen]].<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2007 |title=Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics |encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget  |url=http://www.snl.no/article.html?id=10340445 }}</ref>\n\nThe company offers a range of logistics services, including [[supply chain management]], ocean transportation using [[Neo-bulk cargo]] ships,<ref name=\"WH\">[http://www.2wglobal.com/www/pdf/FleetInternet.pdf Fleet List] (from the Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics website. Accessed 2008-03-11.) [https://web.archive.org/web/20160924172047/http://www.2wglobal.com/globalassets/about-us/documents/fleet-list.pdf Archive]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.2wglobal.com/global-network/fleet/fleet-overview/fleet-list/ |title=Ocean Fleet List|accessdate=24 September 2016 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160920163838/http://www.2wglobal.com/global-network/fleet/fleet-overview/fleet-list/ |archive-date= 20 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wilhelmsenasa.com/aboutus/ourbusiness/thefleet/Pages/Fleetlist.aspx |title=Fleet list, ship details |publisher=|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref> terminal handling, inland distribution and [[technical management|technical services]]. It is one of the world's largest companies in the transporting of [[Roll-on/roll-off]] equipment: automobiles, heavy machinery (mining, construction, farming equipment), yachts, trains, power stations, trailers, [[Mafi roll trailer|Mafi roll trailers]] and others. Headquartered in [[Oslo]] and [[Stockholm]], with main regional offices in [[New York City|New York]], [[Tokyo]] and [[Melbourne]],{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}} the company has 3,300 employees worldwide.<ref name=facts/>\n\nOn 29 October 2008 Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics received the distinguished Norwegian American Trade Award for 2008 from the Norwegian-American Chamber of Commerce.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Norwegian American Trade Award for 2008 |url=http://www.norway.org/business/maritime/wwl.htm  |publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Norway)|Norwegian Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] |date=10 November 2008 |accessdate=20 November 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn '''2017''', Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics were split into Wallenius Wilhelmsen Ocean and Wallenius Wilhelmsen Solutions in the [[Wallenius Wilhelmsen|Wallenius Wilhelmsen Group]].\n\n{{Gallery|lines=3\n|File:Don Quijote.JPG|''Don Quijote'', a WWL [[car carrier]].\n|File:Wallenius Wilhelmsen.JPG|''Trianon'' in the [[Strait of Juan de Fuca]].\n|File:Ship passing through Panama Canal 01.jpg|[[RORO]] carrier ''Tourcoing'' passing through [[Panama canal]].\n}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Taiko (ship)]]\n*[[MV Tricolor]]\n*[[List of roll-on/roll-off vessel accidents]]\n*[[Wallenius Lines]]\n*[[Wilh. Wilhelmsen]]\n*[[American Roll-on Roll-off Carrier]]\n*[[EUKOR]]\n*[[United European Car Carriers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics}}\n*[http://www.2wglobal.com/ Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics official website]\n\n[[Category:1999 establishments in Norway]]\n[[Category:Car carrier shipping companies]]\n[[Category:Commercial management shipping companies]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Wallenius Wilhelmsen Logistics]]\n[[Category:Ro-ro shipping companies]]\n", "name_user": "Birgitfaa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wallenius_Wilhelmsen_Logistics"}
{"title_page": "Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary", "text_new": "{{short description|Protected area in eastern Cambodia}}\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name            = Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary\n| alt_name        = \u178a\u17c2\u1793\u1787\u1798\u17d2\u179a\u1780\u179f\u178f\u17d2\u179c\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c3\u1780\u17c2\u179c\u179f\u17b8\u1798\u17b6, Seima Protection Forest, Seima Biodiversity Conservation Area\n| iucn_category   = \n| iucn_ref        = \n| photo           = Mixed bamboo and semi-evergreen forest in Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary.jpg\n| photo_width     = \n| photo_caption   = Mixed bamboo and semi-evergreen forest in the sanctuary\n| map             = Cambodia\n| relief          = yes\n| map_width       = \n| map_caption     = \n| location        = Cambodia\n| nearest_city    = [[Senmonorom]]\n| coordinates     = {{coords|12.335611|106.842095|region:KH|display=inline, title}}\n| area            = {{convert|2926.9|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\":0\" />\n| established     = 2002\n| visitation_num  = \n| visitation_year = \n| governing_body  = [[Ministry of Environment (Cambodia)|Ministry of Environment]]\n| website         = \n}}\n\n'''Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary''' ([[Khmer language|Khmer]]: \u178a\u17c2\u1793\u1787\u1798\u17d2\u179a\u1780\u179f\u178f\u17d2\u179c\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c3\u1780\u17c2\u179c\u179f\u17b8\u1798\u17b6) is a {{convert|2926.9|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} [[protected area]] in eastern Cambodia, located in [[Mondulkiri Province|Mondulkiri]] and [[Krati\u00e9 Province|Krati\u00e9]] provinces.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://data.opendevelopmentmekong.net/my/dataset/subdecree_no83_on_establishment_of_keo_seima_wildlife_sanctuary/resource/ffcc859e-dbd7-4a26-8dfd-7afd4b269911?view_id=3021dd15-e571-4bfa-b6e7-1b5af20bb512|title=Sub-decree No.83 on Establishment of Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary - Sub-decree No.83 on Establishment of Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary - OD Mekong Datahub|website=data.opendevelopmentmekong.net|language=my|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> The area was first established as Seima Biodiversity Conservation Area in 2002, later becoming Seima Protection Forest in 2009,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://opendevelopmentmekong.net/dataset/?id=sub-decree-no-143-02-09-2009|title=Sub-decree No.143 on Establishment of protected forest and biodiversity conservation Keo Seima in Mondulkiri and Kratie|website=Open Development Mekong|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> finally becoming Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary in 2016.<ref name=\":0\" /> The site is of national, regional, and global importance for a range of biodiversity, with more than 950 species recorded within the protected area.<ref name=\":2\">Griffin, Olly. 2019. The Biodiversity of Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary \u1787\u17b8\u179c\u1785\u1798\u17d2\u179a\u17bb\u17c7\u1793\u17c5\u1780\u17d2\u1793\u17bb\u1784\u178a\u17c2\u1793\u1787\u1798\u17d2\u179a\u1780 \u179f\u178f\u17d2\u179c\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c3\u1780\u17c2\u179c\u179f\u17b8\u1798\u17b6 https://cambodia.wcs.org/DesktopModules/Bring2mind/DMX/Download.aspx?EntryId=37002&PortalId=133&DownloadMethod=attachment</ref> It is also the ancestral and contemporary home of a large number of the [[Pnong people|Bunong]] ethnic group.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Landscape and climate ==\nKeo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary (KSWS) lies between {{convert|60 and 750|m}} above sea level, and is situated in the southeast corner of Cambodia along the border with Vietnam. The northwest section of KSWS forms part of Cambodia's Eastern Plains, while the montane southeast section constitutes the south-western edge of the [[Annamite Range]] range along the Sen Monorom plateau.<ref name=\":3\">Evans, T. D., O\u2019Kelly, H. J., Soriyun, M., Hor, N. M., Phaktra, P., & Pheakdey, S. (2013). Seima Protection Forest. In ''Evidense-based Conservation Lessons from the lower Mekong. Bogor, Indonesia: CIFOR'' (pp. 157\u201386). EarthScan from Routledge.</ref> Major habitat types found within the protected area include [[Tropical evergreen forest|tropical evergreen]], mixed deciduous, [[semi-evergreen]] and deciduous [[Dipterocarp forest]].<ref>Walston, J., Davidson, P., & Soriyun, M. (2001). A Wildlife Survey of Southern Mondulkiri Province, Cambodia, 95.</ref>\n\nAs in much of Cambodia, two main seasons predominate in KSWS: tropical wet and dry. During the wet season, which runs between April to October, the area receives an average of {{convert|2,200-2,800|mm}} of rainfall.<ref name=\":3\" /> Temperatures range annually from {{cvt|16 to 36|\u00b0C}}.\n\n== Biodiversity ==\nMixed forest types and a range of elevation gives rise to a rich collection of biodiversity, both flora and fauna. A total of 959 plant, fungi, and animal species have been recorded in the area,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Griffin|first=Olly|last2=Griffin|first2=Olly|title=Checklist of extant species recorded in Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary, Cambodia|url=https://www.gbif.org/dataset/271be4de-d788-4b18-bde2-4ef4cd80a165|doi=10.15468/rxba17}}</ref> the highest reported number for any Cambodian protected area.<ref name=\":2\" /> A total of 356 bird species have been recorded, exceeding the highest number recorded on [[eBird]] for any site in Cambodia<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>Sullivan, B.L., C.L. Wood, M.J. Iliff, R.E. Bonney, D. Fink, and S. Kelling. 2009. eBird: a citizen-based bird observation network in the biological sciences. Biological Conservation 142: 2282-2292.</ref> and with at least 21 [[Woodpecker|Picidae]] species, KSWS has one of the highest global diversities of any site.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>Styring, A. R. (2002). ''Local, regional, and global patterns of woodpecker (Picidae) diversity: Ecological explanations and practical applications''. Louisiana State University, Louisiana, USA. Retrieved from <nowiki>https://digitalcommons.lsu.edu/gradschool_dissertations/3767</nowiki></ref>\n\nSeven primate species are found in the protected area, including the vast majority of the world's population of the [[Black-shanked douc|black-shanked douc langur]], with an estimated 23,000 individuals.<ref name=\":5\">Nuttall, M., Menghor, N., & O\u2019Kelly, H. (2013). ''Monitoring of key species in the Seima Protected Forest'' (p. 29). Phnom Penh, Cambodia: WCS.</ref> The next largest population, found in Vietnam, is only 500 individuals. A total of 1,200 [[Yellow-cheeked gibbon|southern yellow-cheeked crested gibbon]] are found in the evergreen and semi-evergreen forest areas,<ref name=\":5\" /> including the world's only habituated groups of this species, at Jahoo Gibbon Camp.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://khiri.com/discovery/trekking-to-jahoo-gibbon-camp-in-the-wilds-of-mondulkiri/|title=Trekking to Jahoo Gibbon Camp in the Wilds of Mondulkiri|website=Khiri Travel|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref><ref>Barca, B., & Vincent, C. (2019). ''Field Guide: Jahoo Gibbon Camp''. (H. Washington & Griffin, Olly, Eds.). Andoung Kraloeng, Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary, Mondulkiri, Cambodia: WCS.</ref>\n\nSignificant threatened ungulate populations are present, including [[Eld's deer]], [[sambar deer]], [[banteng]], and the largest living wild bovid, the [[gaur]].\n\nIn 2016, the [[tiger]] was acknowledged as having been driven to extinction in Cambodia, and in KSWS the last record of tiger was from 2006.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=O'Kelly|first=Hannah J.|last2=Evans|first2=Tom D.|last3=Stokes|first3=Emma J.|last4=Clements|first4=Tom J.|last5=Dara|first5=An|last6=Gately|first6=Mark|last7=Menghor|first7=Nut|last8=Pollard|first8=Edward H. B.|last9=Soriyun|first9=Men|last10=Walston|first10=Joe|date=2012-10-15|title=Identifying Conservation Successes, Failures and Future Opportunities; Assessing Recovery Potential of Wild Ungulates and Tigers in Eastern Cambodia|url=https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0040482|journal=PLOS ONE|language=en|volume=7|issue=10|pages=e40482|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0040482|issn=1932-6203|pmc=3471919|pmid=23077476}}</ref>\n\nAt least 15 newly discovered species have been [[Species description|described]] from KSWS (the [[Type locality (biology)|type locality]]); two mammals, two amphibians, two reptiles, and nine insects:<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n* [[Titania's woolly bat]] (''[[Kerivoula titania]]'')\n* Indochinese thick-thumbed bat (''[[Glischropus bucephalus]]'')\n* O'Reang horned frog (\u1780\u1784\u17d2\u1780\u17c2\u1794\u179f\u17d2\u1793\u17c2\u1784\u17a2\u17bc\u179a\u179a\u17b6\u17c6\u1784, ''[[Ophryophryne synoria]]'')\n* Mouhot's litter frog (\u1780\u1784\u17d2\u1780\u17c2\u1794\u179f\u17d2\u179b\u17b9\u1780\u1798\u17bd\u17a0\u17bd\u178f, ''[[Leptobrachium mouhoti]]'')\n* Red-eyed green pit-viper (''[[Trimeresurus rubeus]]'')\n*''Scincella nigrofasciata'', a skink species\n*''Cyana angkorensis'', a moth species\n*''Naarda furcatella'', a moth species\n*''Dichomeris hainanensis'', a moth species\n*''Dichomeris magnimacularis'', a moth species\n*''[[Thubana seimaensis]]'', a moth species\n*''Promalactis apicuncata'', a moth species\n*''Promalactis quadrilobata'', a moth species\n*''Promalactis seimana'', a moth species\n*''Tanna kimtaewooi'', a cicada species\n\nA total of 75 [[threatened species]] (classified as [[Critically endangered]], [[Endangered species|Endangered]], or [[Vulnerable species|Vulnerable]] on the [[IUCN Red List]]) have been recorded as present at the site, as well as 106 [[CITES]] listed species, and 46 species listed as Endangered or Rare under Cambodian law. A total of 28 [[EDGE species]] are found within KSWS, seven species of which are in the global top 100 for their [[Taxonomic groups|taxonomic group]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== National, regional, and global importance ===\nIn addition to having the highest number of species recorded in any Cambodian protected area,<ref name=\":2\" /> KSWS has been highlighted as an area of biodiversity importance under a range of prioritization frameworks.\n\n==== Climate, Community & Biodiversity Alliance ====\nThe Keo Seima [[Reducing emissions from deforestation and forest degradation|REDD+]] project qualifies under the [[Climate, Community & Biodiversity Alliance|Climate, Community & Biodiversity]] (CCB) Standards Gold Level for biodiversity under both vulnerability and irreplaceability criteria.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://registry.verra.org/app/projectDetail/CCB/1650|title=Verra project database. Reduced Emissions From Deforestation And Degradation In Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== Biodiversity hotspot ====\nUnder the framework developed by [[Conservation International]], KSWS forms part of the [[Indo-Burma]] [[Biodiversity hotspot]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Myers|first=Norman|last2=Mittermeier|first2=Russell A.|last3=Mittermeier|first3=Cristina G.|last4=da Fonseca|first4=Gustavo A. B.|last5=Kent|first5=Jennifer|date=2000-02|title=Biodiversity hotspots for conservation priorities|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/35002501|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=403|issue=6772|pages=853\u2013858|doi=10.1038/35002501|issn=1476-4687}}</ref>\n\n==== Endemic Bird Area (EBA), Important Bird Area (IBA) ====\nThe protected area forms part of the EBA 144, South Vietnam Lowlands [[Endemic Bird Area]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://datazone.birdlife.org/eba/factsheet/142|title=BirdLife Data Zone. South Vietnamese lowlands EBA 144.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> recognized for its breeding populations of three restricted-range bird species that characterize the EBA: [[Germain's peacock-pheasant]], [[Orange-necked partridge]] and [[Grey-faced tit-babbler]].\n\nKSWS is also covered parts of two [[Important Bird Area|Important Bird Areas]]: KH026 (the Mondulkiri - Kratie Lowlands)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://datazone.birdlife.org/site/factsheet/mondulkiri--kratie-lowlands-iba-cambodia|title=BirdLife Data Zone. Mondulkiri - Kratie Lowlands|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and KH027 (Snoul / Keo Sema / O Reang).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://datazone.birdlife.org/site/factsheet/snoul--keo-sema--o-reang-iba-cambodia|title=BirdLife Data Zone. Snoul / Keo Sema / O Reang|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> These are prioritized for conservation of [[Orange-necked partridge]], [[Siamese fireback]], [[Green peafowl]], [[White-winged duck]], and [[Great hornbill]], and for vultures, ibises, [[sarus crane]] and green peafowl.\n\n==== Global 200 ====\nUnder the [[Global 200]] priority ecoregions for global conservation, KSWS is included in two areas:<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Olson|first=David M.|last2=Dinerstein|first2=Eric|date=2002|title=The Global 200: Priority Ecoregions for Global Conservation|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/3298564|journal=Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden|volume=89|issue=2|pages=199\u2013224|doi=10.2307/3298564|issn=0026-6493}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Olson|first=David M.|last2=Dinerstein|first2=Eric|date=1998|title=The Global 200: A Representation Approach to Conserving the Earth\u2019s Most Biologically Valuable Ecoregions|url=https://conbio.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1046/j.1523-1739.1998.012003502.x|journal=Conservation Biology|language=en|volume=12|issue=3|pages=502\u2013515|doi=10.1046/j.1523-1739.1998.012003502.x|issn=1523-1739}}</ref>\n\n* Indochina Dry Forests, ecoregion 54. Critical or Endangered.\n* [[Annamite Range]] Moist Forests, ecoregion 25. Vulnerable.\n\n==== Last of the Wild ====\nKSWS is included as one of the 569 [[Last of the Wild]] areas globally that in 1992 - 1995 were found to have been least affected by human activities,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sanderson|first=Eric W.|last2=Jaiteh|first2=Malanding|last3=Levy|first3=Marc A.|last4=Redford|first4=Kent H.|last5=Wannebo|first5=Antoinette V.|last6=Woolmer|first6=Gillian|date=2002-10-01|title=The Human Footprint and the Last of the WildThe human footprint is a global map of human influence on the land surface, which suggests that human beings are stewards of nature, whether we like it or not|url=https://academic.oup.com/bioscience/article/52/10/891/354831|journal=BioScience|language=en|volume=52|issue=10|pages=891\u2013904|doi=10.1641/0006-3568(2002)052[0891:THFATL]2.0.CO;2|issn=0006-3568}}</ref> and again included in the v2 2004 update.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sedac.ciesin.columbia.edu/data/set/wildareas-v2-human-footprint-geographic/data-download|title=Downloads \u00bb Global Human Footprint (Geographic), v2: Last of the Wild, v2 {{!}} SEDAC|website=sedac.ciesin.columbia.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> These areas are:\n\n* [[Southeastern Indochina dry evergreen forests]]\n* [[Central Indochina dry forests]]\n\n==== High Conservation Value Forest ====\nDuring development of the [[Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary#REDD+ project|REDD+ project]] a number of [[High conservation value forest|high conservation values]] were identified:\n\n* HCV1: Forest areas containing globally, regionally or nationally significant concentrations of biodiversity values\n** HCV 1.1: Protected Areas\n** HCV 1.2: Threatened and Endangered Species\n** HCV 1.3: Endemic Species\n* HCV2: Forest areas containing globally, regionally or nationally significant large landscape level forests\n* HCV3: Forest areas that are in or contain rare, threatened or endangered ecosystems\n\n== Communities ==\nUnusually for a protected area in Cambodia, KSWS is home to a large human population, predominately of the [[Pnong people|Bunong]] ethnic group.<ref name=\":3\" /> A traditionally [[Animism|Animist]] group, forests play a large role in community identity. In March 2012, Andoung Kraloeng village in KSWS became the first [[Indigenous peoples|Indigenous]] community in [[Mondulkiri Province]], and third nationally, to receive a collective land title under the 2001 Land Law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cambodia.wcs.org/About-Us/Latest-News/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/705/Seima-village-gains-protection-for-its-land-rights.aspx|title=Seima village gains protection for its land rights|website=cambodia.wcs.org|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://opendevelopmentcambodia.net/news/mondolkiri-minority-group-granted-communal-land-title/|title=Mondolkiri Minority Group Granted Communal Land Title|website=Open Development Cambodia (ODC)|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Since then, a total of 11 indigenous communities have been awarded legal rights to their traditional land within KSWS, facilitated by the [[Wildlife Conservation Society]] and the KSWS project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://opendevelopmentcambodia.net/profiles/indigenous-communities/|title=Registered indigenous communal land|website=Open Development Cambodia (ODC)|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> These titles have already proved vital for communities, allowing them to resist illegal land grabs,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Travers|first=Henry|last2=Winney|first2=Kyle|last3=Clements|first3=Tom|last4=Evans|first4=Tom|last5=Milner-Gulland|first5=E. J.|date=2015-02-01|title=A tale of two villages: An investigation of conservation-driven land tenure reform in a Cambodian Protection Forest|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0264837714002488|journal=Land Use Policy|language=en|volume=43|pages=186\u2013196|doi=10.1016/j.landusepol.2014.11.007|issn=0264-8377}}</ref> with one precedent-setting case reaching the high courts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://programs.wcs.org/asiadrivers/CASE-STUDIES/Cambodia.aspx|title=Cambodia|website=programs.wcs.org|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> \n\n== Management ==\nFrom first establishment in 2002 until 2016, the site was under management as Seima Biodiversity Conservation Area by the Forestry Administration, part of the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries (Cambodia)|Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries]] of the [[Royal Government of Cambodia]].<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2016, all protected areas under management of the Forestry Administration, including what was then Seima Protection Forest, were transferred to management by the [[Ministry of Environment (Cambodia)|Ministry of Environment]] and the sub-national Departments of Environment for [[Mondulkiri Province|Mondulkiri]] and [[Krati\u00e9 Province|Krati\u00e9]] provinces.<ref name=\":0\" /> The area has been supported by the [[Wildlife Conservation Society]] since its inception.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cambodia.wcs.org/|title=WCS Cambodia > Home|website=cambodia.wcs.org|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\n=== REDD+ project ===\nThe majority of KSWS is included in a [[REDD+]] project that is the largest carbon emission reduction program in Cambodia\u2019s land use sector.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://seimaredd.wcs.org/|title=Seima REDD+|website=seimaredd.wcs.org|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Over the 10 year period from 2010 the project is predicted to avoid 17.4 million tons of [[Carbon dioxide equivalent|CO2-e]] emissions,<ref>Reduced Emissions from Deforestation and Degradation in Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary Project Description v7.1 2015. y Wildlife Conservation Society for the Ministry of Environment of the Royal Government of Cambodia https://verra.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/CCB_PROJ_DESC_ENG_C0047_11NOV2016.pdf</ref><ref name=\":7\" /> equivalent to 4 million [[passenger vehicles]] or 4 [[Coal-fired power station|coal-fired power stations]].<ref name=\":6\" /> \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Wildlife sanctuaries of Cambodia]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in Cambodia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Protected area in eastern Cambodia}}\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name            = Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary\n| alt_name        = \u178a\u17c2\u1793\u1787\u1798\u17d2\u179a\u1780\u179f\u178f\u17d2\u179c\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c3\u1780\u17c2\u179c\u179f\u17b8\u1798\u17b6, Seima Protection Forest, Seima Biodiversity Conservation Area\n| iucn_category   = \n| iucn_ref        = \n| photo           = Mixed bamboo and semi-evergreen forest in Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary.jpg\n| photo_width     = \n| photo_caption   = Mixed bamboo and semi-evergreen forest in the sanctuary\n| map             = Cambodia\n| relief          = yes\n| map_width       = \n| map_caption     = \n| location        = Cambodia\n| nearest_city    = [[Senmonorom]]\n| coordinates     = {{coords|12.335611|106.842095|region:KH|display=inline, title}}\n| area            = {{convert|2926.9|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\":0\" />\n| established     = 2002\n| visitation_num  = \n| visitation_year = \n| governing_body  = [[Ministry of Environment (Cambodia)|Ministry of Environment]]\n| website         = \n}}\n\n'''Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary''' ([[Khmer language|Khmer]]: \u178a\u17c2\u1793\u1787\u1798\u17d2\u179a\u1780\u179f\u178f\u17d2\u179c\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c3\u1780\u17c2\u179c\u179f\u17b8\u1798\u17b6) is a {{convert|2926.9|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} [[protected area]] in eastern Cambodia, located in [[Mondulkiri Province|Mondulkiri]] and [[Krati\u00e9 Province|Krati\u00e9]] provinces.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://data.opendevelopmentmekong.net/my/dataset/subdecree_no83_on_establishment_of_keo_seima_wildlife_sanctuary/resource/ffcc859e-dbd7-4a26-8dfd-7afd4b269911?view_id=3021dd15-e571-4bfa-b6e7-1b5af20bb512|title=Sub-decree No.83 on Establishment of Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary - Sub-decree No.83 on Establishment of Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary - OD Mekong Datahub|website=data.opendevelopmentmekong.net|language=my|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> The area was first established as Seima Biodiversity Conservation Area in 2002, later becoming Seima Protection Forest in 2009,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://opendevelopmentmekong.net/dataset/?id=sub-decree-no-143-02-09-2009|title=Sub-decree No.143 on Establishment of protected forest and biodiversity conservation Keo Seima in Mondulkiri and Kratie|website=Open Development Mekong|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> finally becoming Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary in 2016.<ref name=\":0\" /> The site is of national, regional, and global importance for a range of biodiversity, with more than 950 species recorded within the protected area.<ref name=\":2\">Griffin, Olly. 2019. The Biodiversity of Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary \u1787\u17b8\u179c\u1785\u1798\u17d2\u179a\u17bb\u17c7\u1793\u17c5\u1780\u17d2\u1793\u17bb\u1784\u178a\u17c2\u1793\u1787\u1798\u17d2\u179a\u1780 \u179f\u178f\u17d2\u179c\u1796\u17d2\u179a\u17c3\u1780\u17c2\u179c\u179f\u17b8\u1798\u17b6 https://cambodia.wcs.org/DesktopModules/Bring2mind/DMX/Download.aspx?EntryId=37002&PortalId=133&DownloadMethod=attachment</ref> It is also the ancestral and contemporary home of a large number of the [[Pnong people|Bunong]] ethnic group.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Landscape and climate ==\nKeo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary (KSWS) lies between {{convert|60 and 750|m}} above sea level, and is situated in the southeast corner of Cambodia along the border with Vietnam. The northwest section of KSWS forms part of Cambodia's Eastern Plains, while the montane southeast section constitutes the south-western edge of the [[Annamite Range]] range along the Sen Monorom plateau.<ref name=\":3\">Evans, T. D., O\u2019Kelly, H. J., Soriyun, M., Hor, N. M., Phaktra, P., & Pheakdey, S. (2013). Seima Protection Forest. In ''Evidense-based Conservation Lessons from the lower Mekong. Bogor, Indonesia: CIFOR'' (pp. 157\u201386). EarthScan from Routledge.</ref> Major habitat types found within the protected area include [[Tropical evergreen forest|tropical evergreen]], mixed deciduous, [[semi-evergreen]] and deciduous [[Dipterocarp forest]].<ref>Walston, J., Davidson, P., & Soriyun, M. (2001). A Wildlife Survey of Southern Mondulkiri Province, Cambodia, 95.</ref>\n\nAs in much of Cambodia, two main seasons predominate in KSWS: tropical wet and dry. During the wet season, which runs between April to October, the area receives an average of {{convert|2,200-2,800|mm}} of rainfall.<ref name=\":3\" /> Temperatures range annually from {{cvt|16 to 36|\u00b0C}}.\n\n== Biodiversity ==\nMixed forest types and a range of elevation gives rise to a rich collection of biodiversity, both flora and fauna. A total of 959 plant, fungi, and animal species have been recorded in the area,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Griffin|first=Olly|last2=Griffin|first2=Olly|title=Checklist of extant species recorded in Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary, Cambodia|url=https://www.gbif.org/dataset/271be4de-d788-4b18-bde2-4ef4cd80a165|doi=10.15468/rxba17}}</ref> the highest reported number for any Cambodian protected area.<ref name=\":2\" /> A total of 356 bird species have been recorded, exceeding the highest number recorded on [[eBird]] for any site in Cambodia<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>Sullivan, B.L., C.L. Wood, M.J. Iliff, R.E. Bonney, D. Fink, and S. Kelling. 2009. eBird: a citizen-based bird observation network in the biological sciences. Biological Conservation 142: 2282-2292.</ref> and with at least 21 [[Woodpecker|Picidae]] species, KSWS has one of the highest global diversities of any site.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>Styring, A. R. (2002). ''Local, regional, and global patterns of woodpecker (Picidae) diversity: Ecological explanations and practical applications''. Louisiana State University, Louisiana, USA. Retrieved from <nowiki>https://digitalcommons.lsu.edu/gradschool_dissertations/3767</nowiki></ref>\n\nSeven primate species are found in the protected area, including the vast majority of the world's population of the [[Black-shanked douc|black-shanked douc langur]], with an estimated 23,000 individuals.<ref name=\":5\">Nuttall, M., Menghor, N., & O\u2019Kelly, H. (2013). ''Monitoring of key species in the Seima Protected Forest'' (p. 29). Phnom Penh, Cambodia: WCS.</ref> The next largest population, found in Vietnam, is only 500 individuals. A total of 1,200 [[Yellow-cheeked gibbon|southern yellow-cheeked crested gibbon]] are found in the evergreen and semi-evergreen forest areas,<ref name=\":5\" /> including the world's only habituated groups of this species, at Jahoo Gibbon Camp.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://khiri.com/discovery/trekking-to-jahoo-gibbon-camp-in-the-wilds-of-mondulkiri/|title=Trekking to Jahoo Gibbon Camp in the Wilds of Mondulkiri|website=Khiri Travel|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref><ref>Barca, B., & Vincent, C. (2019). ''Field Guide: Jahoo Gibbon Camp''. (H. Washington & Griffin, Olly, Eds.). Andoung Kraloeng, Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary, Mondulkiri, Cambodia: WCS.</ref>\n\nSignificant threatened ungulate populations are present, including [[Eld's deer]], [[sambar deer]], [[banteng]], and the largest living wild bovid, the [[gaur]].\n\nIn 2016, the [[tiger]] was acknowledged as having been driven to extinction in Cambodia, and in KSWS the last record of tiger was from 2006.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=O'Kelly|first=Hannah J.|last2=Evans|first2=Tom D.|last3=Stokes|first3=Emma J.|last4=Clements|first4=Tom J.|last5=Dara|first5=An|last6=Gately|first6=Mark|last7=Menghor|first7=Nut|last8=Pollard|first8=Edward H. B.|last9=Soriyun|first9=Men|last10=Walston|first10=Joe|date=2012-10-15|title=Identifying Conservation Successes, Failures and Future Opportunities; Assessing Recovery Potential of Wild Ungulates and Tigers in Eastern Cambodia|url=https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0040482|journal=PLOS ONE|language=en|volume=7|issue=10|pages=e40482|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0040482|issn=1932-6203|pmc=3471919|pmid=23077476}}</ref>\n\nAt least 15 newly discovered species have been [[Species description|described]] from KSWS (the [[Type locality (biology)|type locality]]); two mammals, two amphibians, two reptiles, and nine insects:<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n* [[Titania's woolly bat]] (''[[Kerivoula titania]]'')\n* Indochinese thick-thumbed bat (''[[Glischropus bucephalus]]'')\n* O'Reang horned frog (\u1780\u1784\u17d2\u1780\u17c2\u1794\u179f\u17d2\u1793\u17c2\u1784\u17a2\u17bc\u179a\u179a\u17b6\u17c6\u1784, ''[[Ophryophryne synoria]]'')\n* Mouhot's litter frog (\u1780\u1784\u17d2\u1780\u17c2\u1794\u179f\u17d2\u179b\u17b9\u1780\u1798\u17bd\u17a0\u17bd\u178f, ''[[Leptobrachium mouhoti]]'')\n* Red-eyed green pit-viper (''[[Trimeresurus rubeus]]'')\n*''Scincella nigrofasciata'', a skink species\n*''Cyana angkorensis'', a moth species\n*''Naarda furcatella'', a moth species\n*''Dichomeris hainanensis'', a moth species\n*''Dichomeris magnimacularis'', a moth species\n*''[[Thubana seimaensis]]'', a moth species\n*''Promalactis apicuncata'', a moth species\n*''Promalactis quadrilobata'', a moth species\n*''Promalactis seimana'', a moth species\n*''Tanna kimtaewooi'', a cicada species\n\nA total of 75 [[threatened species]] (classified as [[Critically endangered]], [[Endangered species|Endangered]], or [[Vulnerable species|Vulnerable]] on the [[IUCN Red List]]) have been recorded as present at the site, as well as 106 [[CITES]] listed species, and 46 species listed as Endangered or Rare under Cambodian law. A total of 28 [[EDGE species]] are found within KSWS, seven species of which are in the global top 100 for their [[Taxonomic groups|taxonomic group]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== National, regional, and global importance ===\nIn addition to having the highest number of species recorded in any Cambodian protected area,<ref name=\":2\" /> KSWS has been highlighted as an area of biodiversity importance under a range of prioritization frameworks.\n\n==== Climate, Community & Biodiversity Alliance ====\nThe Keo Seima [[Reducing emissions from deforestation and forest degradation|REDD+]] project qualifies under the [[Climate, Community & Biodiversity Alliance|Climate, Community & Biodiversity]] (CCB) Standards Gold Level for biodiversity under both vulnerability and irreplaceability criteria.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://registry.verra.org/app/projectDetail/CCB/1650|title=Verra project database. Reduced Emissions From Deforestation And Degradation In Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== Biodiversity hotspot ====\nUnder the framework developed by [[Conservation International]], KSWS forms part of the [[Indo-Burma]] [[Biodiversity hotspot]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Myers|first=Norman|last2=Mittermeier|first2=Russell A.|last3=Mittermeier|first3=Cristina G.|last4=da Fonseca|first4=Gustavo A. B.|last5=Kent|first5=Jennifer|date=2000-02|title=Biodiversity hotspots for conservation priorities|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/35002501|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=403|issue=6772|pages=853\u2013858|doi=10.1038/35002501|issn=1476-4687}}</ref>\n\n==== Endemic Bird Area (EBA), Important Bird Area (IBA) ====\nThe protected area forms part of the EBA 144, South Vietnam Lowlands [[Endemic Bird Area]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://datazone.birdlife.org/eba/factsheet/142|title=BirdLife Data Zone. South Vietnamese lowlands EBA 144.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> recognized for its breeding populations of three restricted-range bird species that characterize the EBA: [[Germain's peacock-pheasant]], [[Orange-necked partridge]] and [[Grey-faced tit-babbler]].\n\nKSWS is also covered parts of two [[Important Bird Area|Important Bird Areas]]: KH026 (the Mondulkiri - Kratie Lowlands)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://datazone.birdlife.org/site/factsheet/mondulkiri--kratie-lowlands-iba-cambodia|title=BirdLife Data Zone. Mondulkiri - Kratie Lowlands|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and KH027 (Snoul / Keo Sema / O Reang).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://datazone.birdlife.org/site/factsheet/snoul--keo-sema--o-reang-iba-cambodia|title=BirdLife Data Zone. Snoul / Keo Sema / O Reang|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> These are prioritized for conservation of [[Orange-necked partridge]], [[Siamese fireback]], [[Green peafowl]], [[White-winged duck]], and [[Great hornbill]], and for vultures, ibises, [[sarus crane]] and green peafowl.\n\n==== Global 200 ====\nUnder the [[Global 200]] priority ecoregions for global conservation, KSWS is included in two areas:<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Olson|first=David M.|last2=Dinerstein|first2=Eric|date=2002|title=The Global 200: Priority Ecoregions for Global Conservation|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/3298564|journal=Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden|volume=89|issue=2|pages=199\u2013224|doi=10.2307/3298564|issn=0026-6493}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Olson|first=David M.|last2=Dinerstein|first2=Eric|date=1998|title=The Global 200: A Representation Approach to Conserving the Earth\u2019s Most Biologically Valuable Ecoregions|url=https://conbio.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1046/j.1523-1739.1998.012003502.x|journal=Conservation Biology|language=en|volume=12|issue=3|pages=502\u2013515|doi=10.1046/j.1523-1739.1998.012003502.x|issn=1523-1739}}</ref>\n\n* Indochina Dry Forests, ecoregion 54. Critical or Endangered.\n* [[Annamite Range]] Moist Forests, ecoregion 25. Vulnerable.\n\n==== Last of the Wild ====\nKSWS is included as one of the 569 [[Last of the Wild]] areas globally that in 1992 - 1995 were found to have been least affected by human activities,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sanderson|first=Eric W.|last2=Jaiteh|first2=Malanding|last3=Levy|first3=Marc A.|last4=Redford|first4=Kent H.|last5=Wannebo|first5=Antoinette V.|last6=Woolmer|first6=Gillian|date=2002-10-01|title=The Human Footprint and the Last of the WildThe human footprint is a global map of human influence on the land surface, which suggests that human beings are stewards of nature, whether we like it or not|url=https://academic.oup.com/bioscience/article/52/10/891/354831|journal=BioScience|language=en|volume=52|issue=10|pages=891\u2013904|doi=10.1641/0006-3568(2002)052[0891:THFATL]2.0.CO;2|issn=0006-3568}}</ref> and again included in the v2 2004 update.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sedac.ciesin.columbia.edu/data/set/wildareas-v2-human-footprint-geographic/data-download|title=Downloads \u00bb Global Human Footprint (Geographic), v2: Last of the Wild, v2 {{!}} SEDAC|website=sedac.ciesin.columbia.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> These areas are:\n\n* [[Southeastern Indochina dry evergreen forests]]\n* [[Central Indochina dry forests]]\n\n==== High Conservation Value Forest ====\nDuring development of the [[Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary#REDD+ project|REDD+ project]] a number of [[High conservation value forest|high conservation values]] were identified:\n\n* HCV1: Forest areas containing globally, regionally or nationally significant concentrations of biodiversity values\n** HCV 1.1: Protected Areas\n** HCV 1.2: Threatened and Endangered Species\n** HCV 1.3: Endemic Species\n** HCV2: Forest areas containing globally, regionally or nationally significant large landscape level forests \n** HCV3: Forest areas that are in or contain rare, threatened or endangered ecosystems\n\n== Communities ==\nUnusually for a protected area in Cambodia, KSWS is home to a large human population, predominately of the [[Pnong people|Bunong]] ethnic group.<ref name=\":3\" /> A traditionally [[Animism|Animist]] group, forests play a large role in community identity. In March 2012, Andoung Kraloeng village in KSWS became the first [[Indigenous peoples|Indigenous]] community in [[Mondulkiri Province]], and third nationally, to receive a collective land title under the 2001 Land Law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cambodia.wcs.org/About-Us/Latest-News/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/705/Seima-village-gains-protection-for-its-land-rights.aspx|title=Seima village gains protection for its land rights|website=cambodia.wcs.org|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://opendevelopmentcambodia.net/news/mondolkiri-minority-group-granted-communal-land-title/|title=Mondolkiri Minority Group Granted Communal Land Title|website=Open Development Cambodia (ODC)|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Since then, a total of 11 indigenous communities have been awarded legal rights to their traditional land within KSWS, facilitated by the [[Wildlife Conservation Society]] and the KSWS project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://opendevelopmentcambodia.net/profiles/indigenous-communities/|title=Registered indigenous communal land|website=Open Development Cambodia (ODC)|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> These titles have already proved vital for communities, allowing them to resist illegal land grabs,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Travers|first=Henry|last2=Winney|first2=Kyle|last3=Clements|first3=Tom|last4=Evans|first4=Tom|last5=Milner-Gulland|first5=E. J.|date=2015-02-01|title=A tale of two villages: An investigation of conservation-driven land tenure reform in a Cambodian Protection Forest|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0264837714002488|journal=Land Use Policy|language=en|volume=43|pages=186\u2013196|doi=10.1016/j.landusepol.2014.11.007|issn=0264-8377}}</ref> with one precedent-setting case reaching the high courts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://programs.wcs.org/asiadrivers/CASE-STUDIES/Cambodia.aspx|title=Cambodia|website=programs.wcs.org|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> \n\n== Management ==\nFrom first establishment in 2002 until 2016, the site was under management as Seima Biodiversity Conservation Area by the Forestry Administration, part of the [[Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries (Cambodia)|Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries]] of the [[Royal Government of Cambodia]].<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2016, all protected areas under management of the Forestry Administration, including what was then Seima Protection Forest, were transferred to management by the [[Ministry of Environment (Cambodia)|Ministry of Environment]] and the sub-national Departments of Environment for [[Mondulkiri Province|Mondulkiri]] and [[Krati\u00e9 Province|Krati\u00e9]] provinces.<ref name=\":0\" /> The area has been supported by the [[Wildlife Conservation Society]] since its inception.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cambodia.wcs.org/|title=WCS Cambodia > Home|website=cambodia.wcs.org|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\n=== REDD+ project ===\nThe majority of KSWS is included in a [[REDD+]] project that is the largest carbon emission reduction program in Cambodia\u2019s land use sector.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://seimaredd.wcs.org/|title=Seima REDD+|website=seimaredd.wcs.org|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Over the 10 year period from 2010 the project is predicted to avoid 17.4 million tons of [[Carbon dioxide equivalent|CO2-e]] emissions,<ref>Reduced Emissions from Deforestation and Degradation in Keo Seima Wildlife Sanctuary Project Description v7.1 2015. y Wildlife Conservation Society for the Ministry of Environment of the Royal Government of Cambodia https://verra.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/CCB_PROJ_DESC_ENG_C0047_11NOV2016.pdf</ref><ref name=\":7\" /> equivalent to 4 million [[passenger vehicles]] or 4 [[Coal-fired power station|coal-fired power stations]].<ref name=\":6\" /> \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Wildlife sanctuaries of Cambodia]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in Cambodia]]\n", "name_user": "Pygathrix nigripes", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHigh Conservation Value Forest", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keo_Seima_Wildlife_Sanctuary"}
{"title_page": "Oudh State", "text_new": "{{About|the state during the British Raj|the natural and historical region in Uttar Pradesh |Awadh}}\n{{redirect|Oudh|the Oudh tree|agarwood|the Arabic musical instrument|Oud}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox country\n|conventional_long_name = British State of Oudh (1801\u20131858)<br> Mughal Subah of Oudh (1732\u20131801)\n|native_name = \n|common_name = Oudh\n|religion = [[Shia Islam]] \n|status = Independent (1732\u20131801)<br> Vassal of the East India Company (1801\u20131858)\n|government_type = Mughal State (1732\u20131816) <br> Princely State (1816\u20131858)\n|event_start =\n|date_start =\n|year_start = 1732\n|event_end = [[Oudh campaign of 1858-9|Oudh campaign]] \n|date_end =  3 Mar \n|year_end = 1859\n|event1 = [[Siege of Cawnpore]]\n|date_event1 = 5 \u2013 25 June 1858\n|event_post = \n|date_post = \n|p1 = Mughal Empire\n|flag_p1 = \n|p2 =British East India Company\n|flag_p2 = Flag of the British East India Company (1801).svg\n|border_p2= no\n|s1 = North Western Provinces \n|flag_s1 = British Raj Red Ensign.svg\n|image_flag =Flag of Awadh.svg \n|image_coat = Oudh-arms short.gif\n|image_map = India1760 1905.jpg\n|image_map_caption = The Kingdom of Oudh in 1760 (Sapphire blue)\n|capital = [[Ayodhya]]<br>[[Faizabad]] <br>[[Lucknow]]\n|common_languages = [[Urdu]] \n|stat_area1             = 62072\n|currency =  rupee\n|representative1        = \n|representative2        = \n|year_representative1   = \n|year_representative2   =\n|title_representative   = \n|leader1 = [[Saadat Ali Khan I]] (first)\n|leader2 = [[Wajid Ali Shah]] (last)\n|year_leader1 = 1722\u20131739\n|year_leader2 = 1856\n|title_leader = [[Nawab of Awadh|Nawab]]\n|footnotes=\n}}\n[[File:Saadut Aly Khan.jpg|thumb|Nawab [[Saadat Ali Khan II]].]]\n[[File:Nasir ud din haidar.jpg|thumb|Nawab [[Nasiruddin Haider]]]]\n[[File:Washah1.jpg|thumb|Nawab [[Wajid Ali Shah]]]]\n[[File:begum hazrat mahal.jpg|thumb|[[Begum Hazrat Mahal]]]]\nThe '''Oudh State''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|a\u028a|d}},<ref>[http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/Oudh Oudh \u2013 definition of Oudh in English from the Oxford dictionary]</ref> also '''Kingdom of Oudh''', or '''Awadh State''') was a [[princely state]] in the [[Awadh]] region of [[North India]] until annexation by the British in 1856. Oudh, the now obsolete but once official English-language name of the state, also written historically as '''Oude''', derived from the name of [[Ayodhya]], its first capital.\n\nAs the [[Mughal Empire]] declined and decentralized, local governors in Oudh began asserting greater autonomy, and eventually Oudh matured into an independent polity governing the fertile lands of the Central and Lower [[Doab]]. With the [[British East India Company]] entering Bengal and decisively defeating Oudh at the [[Battle of Buxar]] in 1764, Oudh fell into the British orbit.\n\nThe capital of Oudh was in [[Faizabad]], but the British Agents, officially known as \"residents\", had their seat in [[Lucknow]]. The Nawab of Oudh, one of the richest princes, paid for and erected a [[Residencies of British India|Residency in Lucknow]] as a part of a wider programme of civic improvements.<ref>Davies, Philip, ''Splendours of the Raj: British Architecture in India, 1660\u20131947.'' New York: Penguin Books, 1987</ref>\n\nOudh joined other Indian states in an upheaval against British rule in 1858 during one of the last series of actions in the [[Indian rebellion of 1857]]. In the course of this uprising detachments of the British Indian Army from the [[Bombay Presidency]] overcame the disunited collection of Indian states in a single rapid campaign. Determined rebels continued to wage sporadic guerrilla clashes until the spring of 1859. This rebellion is also historically known as the ''[[Oudh campaign of 1858-9|Oudh campaign]]''.<ref>Michael Edwardes, ''Battles of the Indian Mutiny,'' Pan, 1963, {{ISBN|0-330-02524-4}}</ref>\n\nAfter the British [[annexation]] of Oudh by the [[Doctrine of Lapse]], the [[North Western Provinces]] became the ''North Western Provinces and Oudh''.<ref>{{cite book |title=Town Planning Regeneration of Cities|author=Ashutosh Joshi|publisher=New India Publishing|date= 1 Jan 2008|isbn=978-8189422820 |page=237 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UFaGME0XDBkC&pg=PA151 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{see also|Oudh Bequest}}\n\n===Establishment===\n[[Saadat Ali Khan I]] was appointed [[Nawab of Oudh]] on 9 September 1722, succeeding [[Girdhar Bahadur]]. He immediately subdued the autonomous [[Shaikhzada]]s of [[Lucknow]] and Raja [[Mohan Singh (king)|Mohan Singh]] of [[Tiloi]], consolidating Oudh as a state. In 1728, Oudh further acquired [[Varanasi]], [[Jaunpur, Uttar Pradesh|Jaunpur]] and surrounding lands from the Mughal noble [[Rustam Ali Khan]] and established stable revenue collection in that province after quelling the chief of [[Azamgarh]], [[Mahabat Khan]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Srivastava |first1=Ashirbadi Lal |title=The First Two Nawabs Of Oudh (a Critical Study Based On Original Sources) |date=1933 |publisher=The Upper India Publishing House, Ltd. |location=Lucknow |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.49871/page/n1}}</ref>{{rp|44}} In 1739 Saadat Khan mobilized Oudh to defend against [[Nader Shah]]'s [[Nader Shah's invasion of the Mughal Empire|invasion of India]], ultimately being captured in the [[battle of Karnal]]. He attempted to cooperate with Nader Shah, but died at Delhi.\n\nIn 1740, his successor [[Safdar Jang]] moved the capital of the state from [[Ayodhya]] to [[Faizabad]].<ref name=\"Gopal1993\">{{cite book|author=Sarvepalli Gopal|title=Anatomy of a Confrontation: Ayodhya and the Rise of Communal Politics in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=47AARF595dUC&pg=PA39|date=15 October 1993|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-1-85649-050-4|pages=39\u2013}}</ref> Safdar Jang gained recognition from Persia after paying tribute. He continued Saadat Khan's expansionist policy, promising military protection to Bengal in exchange for the forts at [[Rohtasgarh]] and [[Chunar]], and annexing portions of [[Farrukhabad]] with Mughal military aid which was ruled by [[Muhammad Khan Bangash]].\n\nAs regional officials asserted their autonomy in [[Bengal]] and the [[Deccan]] as well as with the rise of the [[Maratha Empire]], the rulers of Oudh gradually affirmed their own sovereignty. [[Safdar Jang]] went as far as to control the ruler of Delhi, putting [[Ahmad Shah Bahadur]] on the Mughal throne with the cooperation of other Mughal nobility. In 1748 he gained the [[subah]] of [[Allahabad]] with Ahmad Shah's official support. This was arguably the zenith of Oudh's territorial span.<ref name=\"lal\">{{cite book|last1=Jaswant Lal|first1=Mehta|title=Advanced Study in the History of Modern India: 1707-1813|date=2005|publisher=Sterling Publishers|isbn=9781932705546}}</ref>{{rp|132}} <ref name=\"markovits\">{{Cite book| last=Markovits| first=Claude (ed)| year=2005| title=A History of Modern India 1480\u20131950 (Anthem South Asian Studies)| place=| publisher=Anthem Press.| isbn=1-84331-152-6| url=}}</ref>{{rp|193}}\n\nThe next nawab, [[Shuja-ud-Daula]], further extended Oudh's control of the Mughal emperor. He was appointed [[Vizier|vazir]] to [[Shah Alam II]] in 1762 and offered him asylum after his failed campaigns against the British in the [[Bengal War]].<ref name=\"markovits\"/>\n\n===British contact and control===\nSince Oudh was located in a prosperous region, the [[British East India Company]] soon took notice of the affluence in which the Nawabs of Oudh lived. Primarily, the British sought to protect the frontiers of Bengal and their lucrative trade there; only later did direct expansion occur.\n\n====Shuja-ud-Daula====\n{{Also|Shuja-ud-Daula}}\nBritish dominance was established at the [[Battle of Buxar]] of 1764, when the East India Company defeated the alliance between the nawab of Oudh [[Shuja-ud-Daula]] and the deposed nawab of Bengal [[Mir Kasim]].<ref name=\"ramusack\">{{cite book|last1=Ramusack|first1=Barbara N.|title=The Indian Princes and their States|date=2004|publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref>{{rp|25}} The battle was a turning point for the once rising star of Oudh. The immediate effect was British occupation of the fort at [[Chunar]] and the cession of the provinces of Kora and [[Allahabad]] to Mughal ruler [[Shah Alam II]] under the [[Treaty of Benares (1765)]]. Shaja-ud-Daula further had to pay 5 million rupees as an indemnity, which was paid off in one year.<ref name=\"grover\">{{cite book |last1=Grover |first1=B.L. |last2=Mehta |first2=Alka |title=A New Look at Modern Indian History (From 1707 to the Modern Times) |date=2018 |publisher=S. Chand Publishing |isbn=9789352534340 |edition=32 }}</ref>{{rp|158}}<ref name=\"markovits\" />{{rp|252}} The long-term result would be direct British interference in the internal state matters of Oudh, useful as a buffer state against the [[Marathas]]. The treaty also granted British traders special privileges and exemptions from many customs duties, which led to tensions as British monopolies were established.\n\nShuja-ud-Daula bought the Mughal provinces of Kora and Allahabad in [[Treaty of Benares (1773)]] with the British (who held ''de-facto'' control over the area) for 50 lakh rupees, increased cost of Company mercenaries, and military aid in the [[First Rohilla War]] to expand Oudh as a buffer state against Maratha interests.<ref name=\"ramusack\" />{{rp|65}}<ref name=\"grover\" />{{rp|75}} Done by [[Warren Hastings]], this move was unpopular among the rest of Company leadership, but Hastings continued a harsh policy on Oudh, justifying the military aid as a bid to strengthen Oudh's status as a buffer state against the Marathas. To shape the policy of Oudh and direct its internal affairs Hastings appointed the resident [[Nathaniel Middleton]] in Lucknow that year as well. At the conclusion of the First Rohilla War in 1774, Oudh gained the entirety of [[Rohilkhand]] and the Middle [[Doab]] region, only leaving the independent [[Rampur State]] as a Rohilla enclave.\n\n====Asaf-ud-Daula====\n{{Also|Asaf-ud-Daula}}\nAsaf-ud-Daula acceded to the nawabship of Oudh with British aid in exchange for the [[Treaty of Benares (1775)]] which further increased the cost of mercenaries and ceded the ''sarkars'' of [[Benares]], [[Ghazipur]], [[Chunar]], and [[Jaunpur, Uttar Pradesh|Jaunpur]]. From this time onwards Oudh was consistently compliant with the Company's demands, which continued to demand more land and economic control over the state.<ref name=\"habib\">{{cite journal |last1=Habib |first1=Irfan |last2=Habib |first2=Faiz |title=Mapping the Dismemberment of Awadh 1775-1801 |journal=Proceedings of the Indian History Congress |date=2014 |volume=75 |issue=455-460}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Treaty of Chunar (1781)]] sought to reduce the number of British troops in Oudh's service to cut costs, but failed in this measure due to the instability of Asaf-ud-Daula's rule and thus his reliance on British aid essentially as a puppet regime.<ref name=\"EI\">{{Encyclopaedia of Islam, New Edition|volume=|title=Awadh|page(s)=|first=C. Collin|last=Davies|authorlink=|url=}}</ref>\n\n====Later rulers====\n[[Saadat Ali Khan II]] acceded to throne of Oudh in 1798, owing his seat to British intervention including Governor-General of Bengal [[John Shore, 1st Baron Teignmouth|Sir John Shore]]'s personal proclamation in Lucknow of his rule. A treaty signed on 21 February 1798 increased the subsidy paid to the British to 70 lakh rupees per year.<ref name=\"habib\"/>\n\nIn light of the [[Napoleonic Wars]] and British demands for greater revenue from the Company, in 1801, [[Saadat Ali Khan II]] ceded the entire [[Rohilkhand]] and [[Lower Doab]] as well as the ''sarkar'' of [[Gorakhpur]] under the pressure of [[Lord Wellesley]] to the British in lieu of the annual tribute.<ref>Treaty with the Nawab of Oudh for cession of Territory in commutation of Subsidy, concluded by Henry Wellesley and Lieut.-Col. William Scott 10th Nov. 1801</ref> The cession halved the size of the polity, reducing it to the original Mughal [[subah]] of Awadh (excepting Gorakhpur which was ceded) and surrounded it by directly-administered British territory, rendering it useless as a buffer. The treaty also mandated a government to be put in place that primarily served the citizens of Oudh. It was on the basis of the failure to meet this demand that the British later justified the annexation of Oudh.\n\n[[Farrukhabad]] and [[Rampur State|Rampur]] were not annexed by the British yet; instead they served as separate princely states for the moment.<ref name=\"habib\"/>\n\nThe kingdom became a British [[protectorate]] in May 1816 (However, the state was an unofficial British protectorate since 1764, having little external autonomy). Three years later, in 1819, the [[Ghazi-ud-Din Haidar Shah]] took the title of ''padshah'' (king), signaling formal independence from the Mughal Empire under the advice of the [[Marquis of Hastings]].\n\nThroughout the early 1800s until annexation, several areas were gradually ceded to the British.\n\n===British annexation===\nOn 7 February 1856 by order of [[Lord Dalhousie]], General of the East India Company, the king of Oudh ([[Wajid Ali Shah]]) was deposed, and its kingdom was annexed to British India under the terms of the [[Doctrine of lapse]] on the grounds of alleged internal misrule.<ref name=igi-V-72/>\n\nBetween 5 July 1857 and 3 March 1858 there was an upheaval by the son of the deposed king joining the [[Indian Rebellion of 1857]]. At the time of the rebellion, the British lost control of the territory; they reestablished their rule over the next eighteen months, during which time there were massacres such as those that had occurred in the course of the [[Siege of Cawnpore]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Ben Cahoon |url=http://www.worldstatesmen.org/India_princes_K-W.html#oudh |title=Princely States of India \u2013 Oudh |publisher=Worldstatesmen.org |date= |accessdate=2014-08-08}}</ref><ref>William Barton, ''The princes of India''. Delhi 1983</ref>\n\nAfter Oudh's territory was merged with the ''North Western Provinces'', it formed the larger province of ''North Western Provinces and Oudh''. In 1902, the latter province was renamed the [[United Provinces of Agra and Oudh]], and in 1904 the region within the new ''United Provinces'', corresponding to the former ''North Western Provinces and Oudh'', was renamed the [[Agra Province]].<ref name=igi-V-72>{{Harvnb|Imperial Gazetteer of India vol. V|1908|p=72}}</ref>\n\n==Government==\n\n===Feudatory states===\nThe following were feudatory estates \u2014[[taluqdari]]s<ref>{{cite book|title=The Feudatory and zemindari India, Volume 17, Issue 2|date=1937|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BBYnAQAAIAAJ&q=nanpara&dq=nanpara|accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> or [[pargana]]s\u2014 of Oudh:\n*[[Balrampur Estate]]<ref>[http://members.iinet.net.au/~royalty/ips/b/balrampur.html Balrampur (Taluqdari)]</ref>\n*[[Benares State]] until 1775\n*[[Bhadri Estate]]<ref>[http://members.iinet.net.au/~royalty/ips/b/bhadri.html Bhadri (Taluq)]</ref>\n*[[Itaunja Estate]]<ref>[http://members.iinet.net.au/~royalty/ips/i/itaunja.html Itaunja \u2013 Raipur Ekdaria (Taluq)]</ref>\n*[[Nanpara Taluqdari]]<ref>{{cite book|title=The Indian Year Book, Volume 29|date=1942|publisher=Bennett, Coleman & Company|page=1286|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HV8dAQAAMAAJ&q=nanpara&dq=nanpara|accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Pratapgarh Estate]]\n*[[Tulsipur State]]\n\n===Rulers===\n{{Main|Nawab of Awadh|l1=Nawabs of Oudh}}\n\nThe first ruler of Oudh State belonged to the [[Shia]] Muslim Sayyid Family and descended of [[Musa al-Kadhim]] originated from [[Nishapur]]. But the dynasty also belonged from the paternal line to the [[Kara Koyunlu]] through [[Qara Yusuf]]. They were renowned for their [[secularism]] and broad outlook.<ref>{{cite web|author= Dr. B. S. Saxena |url=http://oudh.tripod.com/misc/noosec.htm |title=Repertoire On Wajid Ali Shah & Monuments of Avadh \u2013 Nawabs of Oudh & their Secularism |publisher= Avadh Cultural Club (Lucknow)|date= 1974}}</ref>\n\nAll rulers used the title of '[[Nawab]]'.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ben Cahoon |url=http://www.worldstatesmen.org/India_princes_K-W.html#Oudh |title=List of rulers of Oudh |publisher=Worldstatesmen.org |date= |accessdate=2014-08-08}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Reign Start !! Reign End !! Name\n|-\n| rowspan = 2 | Subadar Nawab || 1732 || 19 Mar 1739 || Borhan al-Molk Mir Mohammad Amin Musawi Sa\u02beadat \u02beAli Khan I\n|-\n| 19 Mar 1739 || 28 Apr 1748 || rowspan = 3 | [[Safdarjung|Abu'l Mansur Mohammad Moqim Khan]]\n|-\n| Nawab Wazir al-Mamalik || 28 Apr 1748 || 13 May 1753\n|-\n| rowspan = 2 | Subadar Nawab || 5 Nov 1753 || 5 Oct 1754\n|-\n| 5 Oct 1754 || 15 Feb 1762 || rowspan = 2 | [[Shuja-ud-Daula|Jalal ad-Din Shoja\u02be ad-Dowla]] Haydar\n|-\n| rowspan = 5 | Nawab Wazir al-Mamalik || 15 Feb 1762 || 26 Jan 1775\n|-\n| 26 Jan 1775 || 21 Sep 1797 || [[Asaf-ud-Daula|Asaf ad-Dowla Amani]]\n|-\n| 21 Sep 1797 || 21 Jan 1798 || [[Wazir Ali Khan|Mirza Wazir \u02beAli Khan]] \n|-\n| 21 Jan 1798 || 11 Jul 1814 || [[Saadat Ali Khan II|Yamin ad-Dowla Nazem al-Molk]] Sa\u02beadat \u02beAli Khan II Bahadur\n|-\n| 11 Jul 1814 || 19 Oct 1818 || rowspan = 2 | [[Ghazi-ud-Din Haidar Shah|Ghazi ad-Din Rafa\u02beat ad-Dowla]] Abul-Mozaffar Haydar Khan\n|-\n| rowspan = 6 | King (''Padshah-e Awadh, Shah-e Zaman'') || 19 Oct 1818 || 19 Oct 1827\n|-\n| 19 Oct 1827 ||  7 Jul 1837 || [[Nasir-ud-Din Haidar Shah|Naser ad-Din Haydar Solayman]] Jah Shah  \n|-\n| 7 Jul 1837 || 17 May 1842 || [[Muhammad Ali Shah|Mo\u02bein ad-Din Abu'l-Fath Mohammad]] \u02beAli Shah  \n|-\n| 17 May 1842 || 13 Feb 1847 || [[Amjad Ali Shah|Naser ad-Dowla Amjad \u02beAli Thorayya]] Jah Shah  \n|-\n| 13 Feb 1847 || 